 WASHINGTON, June 3 (bdnews24.com/AFP) - President Barack Obama will make his third trip to the Gulf of Mexico region Friday, as the political fallout from the oil disaster mounts and BP makes a desperate bid to plug a gushing undersea well. The visit, announced by the White House will take place just a week after Obama broke a family holiday to fly to Louisiana to inspect damage from the massive spill, which he has branded America's greatest environmental disaster. "President Barack Obama will return to the Louisiana Gulf Coast to assess the latest efforts to counter the BP Deepwater Horizon oil spill," the White House said in a statement Thursday. Obama on Wednesday said that the catastrophe, now threatening beaches in Alabama and Florida, should provide impetus for a fresh effort to push a new energy policy designed to wean America off fossil fuels through Congress. Speculation is also growing that the disaster will prompt the president to call off a scheduled visit to Indonesia and Australia for the second time, after an original journey was put off during the push for health care reform. Obama is expected in the two countries in the middle of the month, but the White House has yet to confirm the dates. The White House is coming under increasing pressure over the oil spill, after holding a rare press conference last week to insist that his government has been engaged in the disaster since it erupted in March. But political critics have been piling on, making comparisons with the terrible political toll that perceived government impotence over Hurricane Katrina exacted on the administration of his predecessor George W. B
